01:03.624 --> 01:05.525
<i>[man]</i>
<i>You know in life when...</i>

01:05.527 --> 01:08.828
<i>...when something disastrous happens,</i>

01:08.829 --> 01:11.063
<i>you go back and replay everything</i>

01:11.064 --> 01:14.500
<i>and you see where
it went wrong?</i>

01:14.501 --> 01:15.969
<i>You're tryin' to figure it out.</i>

01:15.970 --> 01:18.738
<i>You're sifting through
all the little things,</i>

01:18.739 --> 01:20.340
<i>all of the details.</i>

01:20.341 --> 01:22.774
[pop music plays]

01:22.775 --> 01:24.581
[humming along]

01:27.581 --> 01:30.083
<i>One of the details was this house plant</i>

01:30.084 --> 01:33.586
<i>which I picked up
at Trader Joe's.</i>

01:33.587 --> 01:37.926
<i>Another was purchasing
this bottle of poison.</i>

01:38.926 --> 01:40.595
<i>And then there was...</i>

01:41.595 --> 01:43.463
<i>...this kidney,</i>

01:43.464 --> 01:45.998
<i>some sleeping pills,</i>

01:45.999 --> 01:48.735
<i>this transaction
at the bank and...</i>

01:48.736 --> 01:51.604
<i>...clicking onto this
adult internet site</i>

01:51.605 --> 01:56.042
<i>which I had spent many,
many hours enjoying.</i>

01:56.043 --> 01:59.545
<i>But after all was said and done,</i>

01:59.546 --> 02:02.081
<i>you could say my downfall really began</i>

02:02.082 --> 02:05.585
- <i>on a fairytale kind of day...</i>
- <i>[laughing]</i>

02:05.586 --> 02:07.787
<i>...when my wife and I started talking about</i>

02:07.788 --> 02:10.655
<i>having a second child.</i>

02:10.656 --> 02:12.825
<i>The thing was our house.</i>

02:12.826 --> 02:15.528
<i>It had two bedrooms and
we wanted to expand it</i>

02:15.529 --> 02:17.963
<i>to make room for a new nursery.</i>

02:17.964 --> 02:20.032
- <i>So off I went to</i>
- <i>[inaudible]</i>

02:20.033 --> 02:21.869
<i>the Department of Building and Safety,</i>

02:21.870 --> 02:24.504
<i>where I'd be told that our
plans were not to code</i>

02:24.505 --> 02:27.442
<i>and be given this variance
hearing request form.</i>

02:29.442 --> 02:31.178
<i>And although I'm the only one to blame</i>

02:31.179 --> 02:33.781
<i>for the whole big mess you're about to see...</i>

02:34.781 --> 02:36.717
<i>...still I wish
I'd known upfront</i>

02:36.718 --> 02:40.993
<i>about this plate of
cheese and salami.</i>

02:45.993 --> 02:47.493
[man speaking Spanish]

02:47.494 --> 02:48.962
[# Dean Martin:
"Memories Are Made of This"]

02:48.963 --> 02:51.196
♪ <i>Sweet, sweet</i> ♪
♪ <i>Memories you gave-a me</i> ♪

02:51.197 --> 02:54.566
♪ <i>You can't beat</i> ♪
♪ <i>The memories you gave-a me</i> ♪

02:54.567 --> 03:00.742
♪ <i>Take one fresh and tender kiss</i> ♪

03:01.742 --> 03:07.649
♪ <i>Add one stolen night of bliss</i> ♪

03:09.649 --> 03:12.985
♪ <i>One girl, one boy</i> ♪

03:12.986 --> 03:16.189
♪ <i>Some grief, some joy</i> ♪

03:16.190 --> 03:21.493
♪ <i>Memories are made of this</i> ♪

03:21.494 --> 03:22.928
Hey, lookin' good.

03:22.929 --> 03:27.600
- <i># Don't forget a small moonbeam #</i>
- <i>Lookin' good, guys.</i>

03:27.601 --> 03:29.535
<i>Muy bien, amigos.</i>

03:29.536 --> 03:35.611
♪ <i>Fold in lightly with a dream</i> ♪

03:37.611 --> 03:40.512
- <i># Your lips and mine #</i>
- <i>[lawn mower running]</i>

03:40.513 --> 03:42.148
[people cheering]

03:42.149 --> 03:43.749
[glass clinking]

03:43.750 --> 03:45.486
[woman]
Can I have everybody's attention, please?

03:45.487 --> 03:47.587
[man] Quiet, quiet, please.
My gorgeous wife

03:47.588 --> 03:51.157
would like to pontificate
about the happy couple.

03:51.158 --> 03:52.959
- Thank you, thank you.
- Sweetheart.

03:52.960 --> 03:56.963
[clears throat]
Uh, you guys have now been married

03:56.964 --> 03:58.164
for ten years,

03:58.165 --> 04:01.701
which is a very, very, very long time.

04:01.702 --> 04:03.603
Very, very, very long time.

04:03.604 --> 04:05.005
- In a good way.
- In a great way.

04:05.006 --> 04:07.740
Uh-huh.
And, um...

04:07.741 --> 04:10.809
we just really wanna say congratulations.

04:10.810 --> 04:12.945
Jeff, you are...

04:12.946 --> 04:15.215
one of my oldest and dearest friends,

04:16.214 --> 04:18.718
and I'm so happy that you're this lucky in love.

04:18.719 --> 04:21.920
- To Jeff and Nealy!
- [all] To Jeff and Nealy!

04:21.921 --> 04:24.624
Ten more years!

04:24.625 --> 04:28.694
♪ <i>Sweet, sweet</i> ♪
♪ <i>Memories you gave-a me</i> ♪

04:28.695 --> 04:31.931
♪ <i>You can't beat</i> ♪
♪ <i>The memories you gave-a me</i> ♪

04:31.932 --> 04:35.867
♪ <i>With his blessings</i> ♪
♪ <i>from above...</i> ♪

04:35.868 --> 04:38.237
[song fades]

04:38.238 --> 04:39.605
[whispers]
Nealy.

04:39.606 --> 04:42.941
Remember when we were
twenty-two?

04:42.942 --> 04:47.179
We used to F-U-C-K
like three times a day.

04:47.180 --> 04:49.814
[chuckles]
What do you say,

04:49.815 --> 04:53.085
when you get little buddy guy into his bed,

04:53.086 --> 04:56.321
we go relive our youth in ours?

04:56.322 --> 04:58.125
You know, I...

04:59.125 --> 05:01.127
I had so many of those, um,

05:01.128 --> 05:02.929
Copper River salmon finger foods.

05:02.930 --> 05:04.764
[chuckling]
I just...

05:04.765 --> 05:06.373
I really think I'd puke.

05:47.373 --> 05:50.643
<i>Hey, babe.
Thanks for clicking me.</i>

05:50.644 --> 05:52.612
<i>My name is Jasmine Jane.</i>

05:52.613 --> 05:55.280
<i>I think of myself as a tasty fruit</i>

05:55.281 --> 05:59.955
<i>and I would love
to make your banana cry.</i>

06:02.955 --> 06:05.236
[alarm beeping]

06:16.236 --> 06:17.346
[groans]

06:26.346 --> 06:27.913
Nealy.

06:27.914 --> 06:30.086
Come here.

06:33.086 --> 06:35.321
Whoa.

06:35.322 --> 06:37.791
What did this?

06:38.791 --> 06:40.949
No idea.

07:02.949 --> 07:06.387
Hey, Jeff!
You think maybe it's gophers?

07:07.387 --> 07:08.360
[camera clicks]

07:13.360 --> 07:14.927
Nealy.

07:14.928 --> 07:16.362
It's raccoons.

07:16.363 --> 07:18.196
[coughs]

07:18.197 --> 07:19.466
<i>Buenas dias, Senor Lang.</i>

07:19.467 --> 07:22.401
Hey, how's it going, Alma?
You all right?

07:22.402 --> 07:25.771
- I'm going inside, too.
- You're gonna go inside? OK.

07:25.772 --> 07:26.940
Will you say bye to me first?

07:26.941 --> 07:28.908
I gotta go, I gotta go to work.

07:28.909 --> 07:30.975
Ahhh.

07:30.976 --> 07:32.779
<i>[Jeff]</i>
<i>All right, have fun today, OK?</i>

07:32.780 --> 07:34.980
- <i>[boy] OK.</i>
- <i>OK, I love you.</i>

07:34.981 --> 07:36.716
[car alarm beeps]

07:36.717 --> 07:40.120
[boy taunting]

07:41.120 --> 07:43.027
[shouts]

07:48.027 --> 07:49.994
[car beeping]

07:49.995 --> 07:53.032
Whoa! Whoa!

07:53.033 --> 07:54.165
Sorry.

07:54.166 --> 07:55.342
[cat hisses]

08:02.342 --> 08:03.880
[meows]

08:07.880 --> 08:10.152
[sirens blaring]

08:12.152 --> 08:13.319
Hi, Traci.

08:13.320 --> 08:14.521
- Hey, Dr. Lang.
- How you doin'?

08:14.522 --> 08:16.489
- Good.
- Good to see you.

08:16.490 --> 08:17.956
Thank you. [Chuckles]

08:17.957 --> 08:20.267
[chatter, grunts and groans]

08:27.267 --> 08:29.471
Good shot, Doc.
Keep takin' that!

08:31.471 --> 08:34.006
Hey, good playin' tonight,
Doc. You were on fire.

08:34.006 --> 08:35.506
Thanks, man.
What happened to you?

08:35.508 --> 08:37.375
You were lookin' sluggish out there.

08:37.376 --> 08:39.145
Well, that'll happen when you're 50

08:39.147 --> 08:41.313
and workin' double shifts to make ends meet.

08:41.313 --> 08:44.116
But if you wanna hit the weight room right now,

08:44.116 --> 08:45.884
we can see which one of us is stronger.

08:45.885 --> 08:48.121
Oh... no, no, no, no.
I don't wanna embarrass you.

08:48.122 --> 08:49.799
[chuckles]
All right, Doc.

08:58.799 --> 09:01.065
[Jeff]
So we got a notice from the Department

09:01.066 --> 09:02.900
of Building and Safety this morning.

09:02.901 --> 09:04.836
It turns out the city wouldn't even consider

09:04.837 --> 09:06.071
our variance request.

09:06.072 --> 09:08.406
- Oh.
- Yeah. But...

09:08.407 --> 09:10.575
I say screw it.

09:10.576 --> 09:12.377
We go ahead without the permit.

09:12.378 --> 09:14.112
Yeah, but what if we get caught?

09:14.113 --> 09:16.449
I mean, wouldn't we have to
tear it all out and redo it?

09:16.450 --> 09:18.284
It would cost like twice as much.

09:18.285 --> 09:21.853
I'm sure we could avoid getting caught.

09:21.854 --> 09:24.556
What if the whackadoodle neighbor complains?

09:24.557 --> 09:27.325
[chuckles]
The whackadoodle neighbor.

09:27.326 --> 09:29.395
[sighs]
Well...

09:29.396 --> 09:32.936
I think we can persuade her not to.

09:36.936 --> 09:39.505
[knocking]

09:39.506 --> 09:43.109
[dog barking]

09:44.109 --> 09:46.277
Hello.

09:46.278 --> 09:47.847
Hello, Dr. Lang.

09:47.848 --> 09:50.415
- I was just stopping by...
- Quiet, Steven!

09:50.416 --> 09:52.421
[whimpers]

09:55.421 --> 09:56.889
Sorry.

09:56.890 --> 09:58.256
No problem.

09:58.257 --> 10:00.325
So, the reason I was stopping by is

10:00.326 --> 10:03.062
we're planning on doing a little
home improvement next door

10:03.063 --> 10:07.065
and I wanted to apologize
for any inconvenience in advance

10:07.066 --> 10:11.643
and give you this as a token of my appreciation.

10:17.643 --> 10:20.049
It's a beautiful plant.

10:23.049 --> 10:24.583
A lovely flower.

10:24.584 --> 10:30.195
Well, I really tried to pick out
just the perfect one.

10:35.195 --> 10:36.362
Well...

10:36.363 --> 10:39.467
...I should probably
skedaddle.

10:40.467 --> 10:41.474
Bye.

10:48.474 --> 10:50.612
[laughing]

10:52.612 --> 10:54.045
[grunts]

10:54.046 --> 10:57.282
[Nealy] Look!
There's Daddy! [Laughs]

10:57.283 --> 10:58.996
Watch your step.

11:09.996 --> 11:14.532
Now when these little suckers
run down this tree...

11:14.533 --> 11:16.135
[wind chimes chiming]

11:16.136 --> 11:18.037
...I can hear them coming
and I can run outside

11:18.038 --> 11:20.072
and scare the living
S-H-I-T out of them.

11:20.073 --> 11:21.709
Great.

11:22.709 --> 11:24.443
[boy]
Are the raccoons up there?

11:24.444 --> 11:26.079
[Nealy]
Daddy thinks they're up there.

11:26.080 --> 11:28.680
That's why Daddy is spreading
stinky coyote urine

11:28.681 --> 11:31.416
all over to scare them off,

11:31.417 --> 11:35.654
even though we've got tons of
real coyotes all over the place.

11:35.655 --> 11:38.156
Actually, it's mountain lion urine.

11:38.157 --> 11:40.125
Higher up on the food chain,

11:40.126 --> 11:42.026
and I think it smells delicious.

11:42.027 --> 11:44.563
Hey, you know, maybe we should
think about putting in

11:44.564 --> 11:47.232
a series of pathways and pocket gardens,

11:47.233 --> 11:50.512
like out front, and not give the
raccoons anything to turn over.

11:59.512 --> 12:00.650
[footsteps running]

12:03.650 --> 12:04.750
[grunts]

12:04.751 --> 12:06.335
[wind chimes chiming]

12:23.335 --> 12:25.376
[rustling]

12:29.376 --> 12:31.681
[raccoon chittering]

12:35.681 --> 12:37.223
[whispering]
Go.

12:43.223 --> 12:44.368
[hisses]

12:55.368 --> 12:58.373
[whispering]
Hey! Drop that!

13:00.373 --> 13:01.276
[whispering]
Stop!

13:03.276 --> 13:05.511
[whispering]
Come on!

13:05.512 --> 13:08.430
[whispering]
Fucker!

13:24.430 --> 13:25.664
Hey, Doc.

13:25.665 --> 13:28.534
Hey, Lincoln, what's up?
Where is everybody?

13:28.535 --> 13:30.204
Don't know, Doc.
No one showed up yet.

13:31.204 --> 13:32.503
How's the baby business?

13:32.504 --> 13:33.705
- It's good.
- Yeah?

13:33.706 --> 13:35.841
- Yeah.
- Gotta warm up.

13:35.842 --> 13:37.409
How's everything for you?

13:37.410 --> 13:38.744
You, uh, you still workin' at that nightclub?

13:38.745 --> 13:40.445
Oh, no.

13:40.446 --> 13:43.381
Quit that a while back, too much strife.

13:43.382 --> 13:45.285
Working for the, uh,
Manufacturers Mineral Company...

13:45.286 --> 13:48.152
hauling, uh, rocks and gravel.

13:48.153 --> 13:49.287
It's been cool.

13:49.288 --> 13:50.721
I was gonna ask you about that shirt,

13:50.722 --> 13:52.658
- but it says "Leonard" on it.
- That's my name, Doc.

13:52.659 --> 13:56.127
Lincoln's just a nickname my
teammates gave me in college.

13:56.128 --> 13:57.728
- Basketball teammates?
- Yep.

13:57.729 --> 13:59.765
They used to call me "Link"

13:59.766 --> 14:02.300
because, uh, when I joined the squad,

14:02.301 --> 14:05.771
fellas said they no longer had
a weak link in the lineup.

14:05.772 --> 14:08.574
Then that became "Lincoln,"

14:08.575 --> 14:11.642
because I led 'em out of the
slavery of a third place team.

14:11.643 --> 14:15.280
I guess it doesn't surprise me
you were such a stud in college.

14:15.281 --> 14:17.249
- Yeah?
- When we first started playing together,

14:17.250 --> 14:20.352
- before you got old and slow.
- Oh, damn, man. [Laughs]

14:20.353 --> 14:24.189
I, uh, I thought you played well
enough to have been pro.

14:24.190 --> 14:26.724
I almost did, Doc, but it wasn't in the cards.

14:26.725 --> 14:28.327
Huh. Why not?

14:28.328 --> 14:29.229
Well, I'll tell you the story
if you want to hear it.

14:30.229 --> 14:32.564
- Yeah, sure.
- All right.

14:32.565 --> 14:34.732
Whoo. Good shot.

14:34.733 --> 14:36.503
It was my sophomore year...

14:37.503 --> 14:39.271
...and we had a real good team.

14:39.272 --> 14:41.208
I mean, real good.

14:42.208 --> 14:44.343
We had, uh, just won the big game.

14:44.344 --> 14:46.578
- Clinched our conference.
- Wow.

14:46.579 --> 14:49.714
And, uh... damn.

14:49.715 --> 14:52.416
It was like a dream, Doc.

14:52.417 --> 14:55.687
Like a real dream.

14:55.688 --> 14:59.424
[muffled]
They get in this huge car accident and that's it.

14:59.425 --> 15:00.792
That's it.
His career's over.

15:00.793 --> 15:02.327
It's like over

15:02.328 --> 15:05.597
and like right, right
when he would turn pro, too.

15:05.598 --> 15:08.534
It's, it's, it's like a crusher.

15:08.535 --> 15:11.670
He's always got these pieces
of gauze taped to his arm.

15:11.671 --> 15:14.740
Turns out the poor guy's got kidney failure.

15:14.741 --> 15:16.208
[toilet flushes]

15:16.209 --> 15:18.443
Jesus.

15:18.444 --> 15:21.646
It's amazing how you can know
someone for so long,

15:21.647 --> 15:24.782
but you never really know 'em.

15:24.783 --> 15:26.217
Wow.

15:26.219 --> 15:27.452
[spits]

15:27.453 --> 15:31.323
He's got these terrible, cracked teeth.

15:31.324 --> 15:34.325
I was thinking about paying
for him to go to the dentist,

15:34.326 --> 15:37.663
but I don't know.

15:37.664 --> 15:41.300
Well, you know, if his passion's
really basketball...

15:41.301 --> 15:42.734
- Mmm. [Spits]
- ...you should talk to Ron's sister

15:42.735 --> 15:44.269
about that school she runs.

15:44.270 --> 15:46.275
Maybe they have a coaching job open.

15:49.275 --> 15:51.845
That's not a bad idea.

15:53.845 --> 15:55.217
[knocking]

15:57.217 --> 15:58.282
Hi.

15:58.283 --> 15:59.885
Sorry to bother you,
Dr. Lang,

15:59.886 --> 16:03.789
but when your guys broke
through your wall the other day

16:03.790 --> 16:05.724
a bunch of dust got into my house.

16:05.725 --> 16:07.228
Oh. I'm really sorry
about that.

16:08.228 --> 16:09.660
[dog whines]

16:09.661 --> 16:11.329
I also, I, I noticed that you're

16:11.330 --> 16:12.965
expanding your front room towards our house.

16:12.966 --> 16:15.601
- Right.
- I looked it up for me on the internet.

16:15.602 --> 16:18.640
The code is to leave a five foot passage.

16:20.640 --> 16:22.574
[dog growls]

16:22.575 --> 16:23.976
What can I do?

16:23.977 --> 16:26.011
You can't see it anymore because I spent hours

16:26.012 --> 16:28.880
cleaning everything with
white vinegar and a toothbrush.

16:28.881 --> 16:33.352
[chuckles]
But you can see it on the TV here.

16:33.353 --> 16:35.454
Oh.

16:35.455 --> 16:38.022
Wow, well, I can have the guys
working on my project

16:38.023 --> 16:39.591
come by and clean up for you.

16:39.592 --> 16:43.661
I hardly think that a, a laborer

16:43.662 --> 16:45.430
who hammers and saws all day would know

16:45.431 --> 16:46.897
how to clean my house.

16:46.898 --> 16:48.868
Yeah, you might be right about that.

16:48.869 --> 16:50.901
And this has been very, very hard on me.

16:50.902 --> 16:54.039
I mean, with all this dust just,
it's just floating around.

16:54.040 --> 16:56.275
Just look!
It's everywhere! See?

16:56.276 --> 16:59.580
It's everywhere!
Here, you see it?

17:00.580 --> 17:01.746
I mean, you're a doctor.

17:01.747 --> 17:03.447
You've heard of environmental illnesses.

17:03.448 --> 17:05.852
- Sure, I've heard of 'em.
- That's, that's why I keep this

17:05.853 --> 17:08.654
basil leaf pinned to my lapel.
It purifies the air.

17:08.655 --> 17:11.957
[inhales deeply]
My naprapath suggested it.

17:11.958 --> 17:13.758
It's been a lifesaver.

17:13.759 --> 17:16.661
Well, I'm very happy to pay for
a professional cleaning service

17:16.662 --> 17:18.330
if you need it.
Whatever the cost.

17:18.332 --> 17:20.431
You give me the bill, I'll write the check.

17:20.432 --> 17:22.402
I just want you to be happy.

17:23.402 --> 17:25.002
That's very nice of you.

17:25.003 --> 17:27.506
Not at all.

17:27.507 --> 17:29.441
All right, I should get goin', so...

17:29.442 --> 17:30.941
- Dr. Lang?
- Yeah?

17:30.942 --> 17:32.842
I heard you last night...
[chuckles]

17:32.843 --> 17:34.814
...try to scare away
your raccoons.

17:34.815 --> 17:37.048
Oh, I'm sorry about that.

17:37.049 --> 17:38.683
[chuckling]
That's OK.

17:38.684 --> 17:39.986
I don't sleep much anyway.

17:39.987 --> 17:42.520
- You don't sleep?
- No.

17:42.521 --> 17:45.459
I get a little every few weeks, but...

17:46.459 --> 17:48.327
...basically
I'm a night creature.

17:48.328 --> 17:49.660
Huh.

17:49.661 --> 17:52.430
Well, I could get you some samples of Ambien

17:52.431 --> 17:53.932
from the office.
It might help with that.

17:53.933 --> 17:55.433
- Really?
- Yeah.

17:55.434 --> 17:56.634
You know what?

17:56.635 --> 17:58.104
I'll drop 'em in your mailbox

17:58.105 --> 17:59.679
when I get home from work.

18:06.679 --> 18:09.526
[whistling]

18:20.526 --> 18:23.862
[grunts and groans]
Nealy!

18:23.863 --> 18:25.863
Wow, this stuff is burning the skin of my hand

18:25.864 --> 18:27.669
just touching it!

